My thought is very similar to the solution of this problem https://leetcode.com/problems/maximum-sum-of-3-non-overlapping-subarrays/.

Define dp state:

`dp[i][j]: when use i carpet, starting from j-th floor, the maximum covered white tiles.`

The relation between dp states:

`dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j-k] + # of covered white tiles by i-th carpet.`
`i-1` is the number of carpet used 
`j-k` is the maximum possible starting floor for `i-1` floors. (The best strategy is not to overlap the carpets).

To quickly get the # of covered white tiles by i-th carpet, we need to calculate the prefix sum of white tiles.


Remember we want to find the maximum covered white tiles.
If after the i-th carpet covered tile starting from position j,
the overall covered white tiles are not better than previous result,
previous result should be used. So we have the following relation:

`dp[i][j] = max(dp[i][j], dp[i][j-1]);`


Example:
```
floor:
1 1 0 0 0 1 0 1 0

carpet len: 2, num carpets: 1

dp[1] = [2 2 2 2 2 2 2 2 2]
```

```
class Solution {
public:
    int minimumWhiteTiles(string floor, int numCarpets, int carpetLen) {
        int m = numCarpets, n = floor.length(), k = carpetLen;
        vector<vector<int>> dp(m+1, vector<int>(n+1, 0));
        vector<int> presum(n+1, 0);
        floor = "#" + floor;
        int count = 0;
        for(int i=1; i<=n; i++) {
            count += (floor[i]-'0');
            presum[i] = presum[i-1]+(floor[i]-'0');
        }

        int ret = count;
        for(int i=1; i<=m && ret>0; i++) {
            for(int j=(i-1)*k+1; j<=n && ret>0; j++) {
                dp[i][j] = (i==1?0:dp[i-1][j-k]) + presum[min(n,j+k-1)] - presum[j-1];
                dp[i][j] = max(dp[i][j], dp[i][j-1]);
                ret = min(ret, count - dp[i][j]);
            }
        }
        return ret;
    }
};
```

