# Explaination
1) Initialize $$closest$$ with the first element of the array.

2) Iterate through the array, comparing the absolute values of each element with the absolute value of $$closest$$.

- Calculate the absolute value of $$current$$ using the $$abs()$$ function.

- If the absolute value of the $$current$$ element is smaller than the absolute value of $$closest$$, update $$closest$$ to the current element.

- If the absolute values are equal, compare the actual values of the $$current$$ element and $$closest$$. If the $$current$$ element is greater, update $$closest$$ to the $$current$$ element.

3. After iterating through all elements, $$closest$$ holds the number closest to zero in terms of its absolute value.

4. Return $$closest$$ as the result.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
O(n)

- Space complexity:
O(1)

# Cpp Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int findClosestNumber(std::vector<int>& nums) {
        int closest = nums[0]; 

        for (int i = 0; i < nums.size(); i++) {
            int current = nums[i];

            if (abs(current) < abs(closest) || (abs(current) == abs(closest) && current > closest)) {
                closest = current;
            }
        }

        return closest;
    }
};

```
