solutions.content:
# Intuition
It's faster to consider each lattice point, and see if it fits in any circle, than it is to consider each circle, generate points inside it, and then try to dedup.

Otherwise, we're just drawing a bounding box that covers the maximum range of points that circles could encompass, and checking each point against each circle until we find one it fits in.

# Approach
Since we're just comparing against r squared every time, we can save on multiplication costs by storing r_sq along with the Circle object.

Creating a BoundingBox type gives us a more ergonomic way to find that largest bounding box using reduce() and iterate over all interior lattice points.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(m * n), for the m x n bounding box containing all the circles. We have to check each point against at least one circle.

- Space complexity: O(circles.len()). Technically this could be done in O(1) space if we didn't 

# Code
```
impl Solution {
    pub fn count_lattice_points(circles: Vec<Vec<i32>>) -> i32 {
        let circles = circles
        .into_iter()
        .map(|v| Circle::new(v[0], v[1], v[2]))
        .collect::<Vec<Circle>>();

        let bounding_box = circles
        .iter()
        .map(|circle| circle.bounding_box())
        .reduce(|a, b| a.merge(b))
        .unwrap_or_default();

        bounding_box
        .into_lattice_iter()
        .filter(|&(i, j)| {
            circles.iter().any(|circle| circle.contains(i, j))
        })
        .count() as i32
    }
}

struct Circle {
    pub x: i32,
    pub y: i32,
    pub r: i32,
    pub r_sq: i64,
}

impl Circle {
    fn new(x: i32, y: i32, r: i32) -> Self {
        let r_sq = i64::from(r) * i64::from(r);
        Self { x, y, r, r_sq}
    }

    fn bounding_box(&self) -> BoundingBox {
        BoundingBox {
            min_x: self.x - self.r,
            max_x: self.x + self.r,
            min_y: self.y - self.r,
            max_y: self.y + self.r,
        }
    }

    fn contains(&self, i: i32, j: i32) -> bool {
        let x_distance: i64 = (i - self.x).into();
        let y_distance: i64 = (j - self.y).into();
        x_distance * x_distance + y_distance * y_distance <= self.r_sq
    }
}

#[derive(Default, Clone, Copy)]
struct BoundingBox {
    min_x: i32,
    max_x: i32,
    min_y: i32,
    max_y: i32,
}

impl BoundingBox {
    pub fn merge(self, other: Self) -> Self {
        Self {
            min_x: self.min_x.min(other.min_x),
            max_x: self.max_x.max(other.max_x),
            min_y: self.min_y.min(other.min_y),
            max_y: self.max_y.max(other.max_y),
        }
    }

    pub fn into_lattice_iter(self) -> impl Iterator<Item = (i32, i32)> {
        (self.min_x..=self.max_x)
        .flat_map(move |i| (self.min_y..=self.max_y).map(move |j| (i, j)))
    }
}
