solutions.content:
Hmm, I guess a little bit overthinking did bring the speed up. So I was worried that I have lots of circles that centre at the same point, then I decided to remove them first. Hence, we have this algorithm that is fairly fast.

So first, we group keep only one circle if multiple is centred at the same point. We keep the largest one of course. Then we just go through each circle, and go through each possible point, and add them to a set.

```python
class Solution:
    def countLatticePoints(self, circles: List[List[int]]) -> int:
        found = set()
        distance = lambda x, y, cx, cy: (x - cx)**2 + (y - cy)**2
        centre_to_radius = {}
        for x, y, radius in circles:
            centre_to_radius[x, y] = max(centre_to_radius.get((x, y), -1), radius)
        for (centre_x, centre_y), radius in centre_to_radius.items():
            for x in range(centre_x - radius, centre_x + radius + 1):
                for y in range(centre_y - radius, centre_y + radius + 1):
                    if (x, y) not in found\
                    and distance(x, y, centre_x, centre_y) <= radius * radius:
                        found.add((x, y))
        return len(found)
