I found that many people use set<pair<int, int>> for simplicity, but it is not reasonable to order these coordinates. Although unordered_set<pair<int, int>> is not supported by default, we can assign a proper hash function to it as we know that the range of 0 <= x, y <= 100. Then by brute force checking them, we have the following solution.

(Note that if you try a bad hash function such as pair<int, int> p => p.first ^ p.second, this would lead to tons of hash value confliction and then TLE.)
```
class hashFunction {
public:
    size_t operator()(const pair<int , int> &x)const {
        return x.first * 1000 + x.second;
    }
};

class Solution {
public:
    int countLatticePoints(vector<vector<int>>& circles) {
        unordered_set<pair<int, int>, hashFunction> uset;
        for (auto& circle : circles) {
