# Solution 

```C++
class Solution {
public:
    string removeDigit(string number, char digit) {
        int pos = -1, n = number.size();
        for(int i = n-1; i>=0;i--) {
            if((number[i] == digit) && (pos == -1 || number[i+1]>number[i])) {
                pos = i;
            }
        }
        return number.erase(pos,1);
    }
};
```

# Observation
*(1) The left-most digit greater than its right neighbor*

When
```
digit = '3'  and number "14323938"
```
You just need to delete the first digit=3 which is greater than its right element.
Then you can get the answer is 
```
1432_938. 
```

*(2) Otherwise, consider the right-most digit*

But if there is not exist first digit which is greater than its right element,  then
you just need to delete the last digit to get the answer.
For example,
```
digit = '3'  and number= "143233138"
```

the answer is 
```
1432331_8
```
.

# Code Explanation
I set pos = -1 first.
In my loop, it running from the most right to most left. 
So it will set the pos int\xF4 the last digit in number first. 
If there is digit in front of pos  that larger than its right neighbor, then update pos. 
So the pos can be the pos of first digit which is greater than its right neighbor if the such pos exist.

Some people may ask that should I need to check the boundary of  i+1. 
```number[i+1]>number[i]```
In our loop structure, we don't need to check i+1<n because the code will check the truth of pos==-1 
first when right-most element of string is the same as to digit. So we can save time to check ```i+1<n```




# Complexity Analysis 
*Time Complexity O(N)*
The loop only travel from right-most element to left-most element. 
And each operation in it using O(1)
So the total time complexity is O(N) in worst case.
*Space Complexity O(1)*
After finding the pos, it erase internal char in string and return the string itself.
So space complexity is O(1). 

