// after one digit deleted, no matter which digit deleted, new number has the length of n - 1.
// we want the new number greater than the old.

// if we delete the digit at index (i), compare with the (i + 1) , 

// if (i + 1) > (i), (i + 1) will subtitute the (i), and the new number is greater than the old.
//     EX -> 1114999, digit = 4, we got 111999, 1119 > 1114
//     For we search the digit starting from the most significant index, the first deletion is it.


// if (i + 1) < (i), the new one is less than the old, so don't do anything to it for now. 
// Just record the index, if it is the only targer digit, it is the only number to delete.

// if (i + 1) == (i), (i + 1) means the consecutive number, the change depands on the next non-target digit. Just find the last one.
public String removeDigit(String number, char digit) {
	// using StringBuffer, StringBuffer is more efficient to delete.
	// (String also works, needs more codes and overhead)
	StringBuffer sb = new StringBuffer(number);

	// to record the last occured digit
	int last = 0;

	// search the digit starting from most significant index
	for (int i = 0; i < sb.length(); i++) {

		// if we find the digit, compare with the next digit(i, i + 1)
		// A: i != sb.length() - 1 : compare with the next digit, so i can't reach to i - 1
		// B: sb.charAt(i) == digit && sb.charAt(i + 1) != digit, ignore the consecutive one, preocess the last.
		if (i != sb.length() - 1 && sb.charAt(i) == digit && sb.charAt(i + 1) != digit) {

			// find the next is greater
			if (sb.charAt(i + 1) >= sb.charAt(i)) {
				return sb.deleteCharAt(i).toString();
			}
		}
		// record the last index, if it is only one digit.
		if (sb.charAt(i) == digit)
			last = i;
	}

	// there is only one digit, delete it.
	return sb.deleteCharAt(last).toString();
}
