solutions.content:
I almost spent the whole day on this question :(
I am not as smart as the most voted posts but here's what i learned from this prolem.

1) Sliding window is tricky to implement especially with multiple moving parts. I often trip myself when implementing it. The trick i learned is to have at least one for loop to process one state at a time. When processing this state, focus on this state. For example in this question, each for loop focuses on a single tile segment. We add it no matter what, and then discuss the condition how to move the starting tile to fix it.
```
start = 0
for (end in 0 to i) {
     process the end value

	 while (condition is not met) {
	     process start value
	 }

	 (optional) double check if condition is still met {
	     update the answer
	 }

}
```


2) Sliding window doesn't mean you have to loop the window position, the window can be the condition and we loop the inputs. This is where i missed when i started on my own. After quickly read other people's post, I discovered this idea and switched back to my own implementation.

3) the Math.max(start, toRemove[0]) is also tricky. We must remember which part of the start segment has been removed. Otherwise, it is a double counting error. I spent hours debugging cuz i was able to pass 90% of the test cases. Eventually i found out i missed the use case where we moved the window multiple times in the same segment.


4) I hate this type of interval / segment problems.. So hard to count the boundary. Fingers crossed i won't run into one during onsite interview :)


```
class Solution {
    public int maximumWhiteTiles(int[][] tiles, int carpetLen) {        
        // alternative solution: 
        // loop through the tiles instead of the window
        // every new tile we try to add it to the existing window
        // if we can add whole, great
        // if we can add part of it, we just add all of it and shrink the window start
        // we need to move up the window to make sure we can continue to add more tiles
        Arrays.sort(tiles, (a, b) ->{
            // just to make sure input is not trolling us
            return Integer.compare(a[0], b[0]);
        });


        int max = 0;
        int start = tiles[0][0]; // window start at the first tile segment start
        int end = 0; // window end
        int sum = 0; // window sum
        int j = 0;  // tile pointer
        for (int i = 0; i < tiles.length; ++i) {
            // just add the whole tile no matter what
            int[] t = tiles[i];
            end = t[1];
            sum += (t[1] - t[0] + 1);
            // window might be over expanded
            while (end - start + 1 > carpetLen) {
                // move up the carpet to at least cover the current one
                // several possibilities
                // try to remove start until the window is good again
                int[] toRemove = tiles[j];
                int newStart = end - carpetLen + 1; // min starting position, we must start on this position to have a valid window
                // we can remove the next tile entirely
                if (toRemove[1] < newStart) {
                    sum -= (toRemove[1] - Math.max(start, toRemove[0]) + 1);
                    ++j;
                    start = tiles[j][0]; // skip any empty spaces since they don't matter
                } else {
                    // we cannot just remove the whole tile, move our start window pointer to the min position
                    sum -= (newStart - Math.max(start, toRemove[0]));
                    start = newStart;
                }
            }

            max = Math.max(max, sum);
        }
        return max;
    }
}
```

