solutions.content:
First we can realize that we only would start the carpet at the start of a tile-set. If we started in the middle of a set, n tiles from the start, then we loose out on the first n tiles and could at most have only covered n new tiles, so we may as well have started at the left most tile in the set instead. So we can try placing the carpet at the start of each tile set and see which one covers the most tiles.

If we have a long carpet, when we go from the start of one tile-set to the next, we might fully or partially cover some other tile-set in both cases (spots with `|` mark the tiles that are covered in both cases):
```
cccccccccccccccccc
wwww www    wwww   wwww
     |||    ||||
     cccccccccccccccccc
wwww www    wwww   wwww
```

Rather than recalculating this fact, we can just check what's newly covered and what's now uncovered by keeping track of the previous starting and ending postions of the carpet (spots with `|` mark newly uncovered or covered tiles):
```
cccccccccccccccccc
wwww www    wwww   wwww
|||||             |||||
     cccccccccccccccccc
wwww www    wwww   wwww
```

We always uncover the whole last tile-set (in the above example, the first 4 white tiles) since we move the the start of the next tile-set. Then we calculate what the n new tiles to the left of the last ending tile cover. In this way we will only process each tile-set once and so besides the initial sorting of tiles, the counting takes O(N) time.

```
class Solution
{
  public:
    int maximumWhiteTiles(vector<vector<int>> &tiles, int carpetLen)
    {
        sort(tiles.begin(), tiles.end());

        // Initialized so that the first tile starts "fresh"
        int lastStart = -carpetLen;
        int lastEnd = -1;
        int lastEndTileIndex = 0;
        int covered = 0;
        int maxCovered = 0;

        for (int i = 0; i < tiles.size(); ++i)
        {
            if (i != 0)
            {
                // Remove the last tile-set that we started from
                covered -= tiles[i - 1][1] - tiles[i - 1][0] + 1;
            }

            int newStart = tiles[i][0];
            int increase = min(newStart - lastStart, carpetLen);
            int sudoStart = max(newStart, lastEnd + 1);
            int sudoEnd = sudoStart + increase - 1;

            // While the end of the additional carpet lenth covers at least 1 tile in the current set, mark those as covered and then try the next set.
            while (lastEndTileIndex < tiles.size() && sudoEnd >= tiles[lastEndTileIndex][0])
            {
                covered += min(sudoEnd, tiles[lastEndTileIndex][1]) - max(sudoStart, tiles[lastEndTileIndex][0]) + 1;
                ++lastEndTileIndex;
            }

            maxCovered = max(maxCovered, covered);

			// When the carpet ends in the middle of a set, the while loop will have gone 1 set too far
			if (sudoEnd <= tiles[lastEndTileIndex - 1][1])
            {
                --lastEndTileIndex;
            }
			// Once the end of the carpet is past the last tile in the last tile-set, starting the carpet any further to the right will only remove tiles
            else if (lastEndTileIndex == tiles.size())
            {
                break;
            }

            lastStart = newStart;
            lastEnd = sudoEnd;
        }

        return maxCovered;
    }
};
```

