# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
It's always better to put the carpet at the beginning of an interval so we can try to align the left border of the carpet with every starting point of segments.

However, the last overlapping segment may be partially covered, so I split the covered segments into two categories
1. completely covered segments and
2. partially covered segments

and keep track number of these tiles respectively.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
It could take O(n) to find the completely/partially covered tiles for each starting point. However, the greater the starting point, the last covered tiles must be greater or equal to the previous one.

Due to the abovementioned trend, sliding window method is taken into consideration. 

1. Sort the disjoint tile segment using their starting point
2. Iterate through all the possible staring point of the carpet and keep a sliding window with a right pointer on the first non-completely overlapping segment.
3. Update the right pointer and compute the number of completely/partially covered tiles
4. Update `max_covered_tiles`
5. Slide the left boundary and update the number of completely/partially covered tiles

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
Sorting $O(n\log n)$
Sliding Window $O(n)$

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
$O(quicksort)$

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int maximumWhiteTiles(vector<vector<int>>& tiles, int carpetLen) {
        ::sort(tiles.begin(), tiles.end());
        int complete = 0, partial = 0, n = tiles.size(), max_cover_len = 0;
        for (int l = 0, r = 0; l < n; ++l) {
            // cleft := left border of the carpet, cright := right boundary
            int cleft = tiles[l][0], cright = tiles[l][0] + carpetLen - 1;

            // add as much complete segment as possible 
            for (; r < n && tiles[r][1] <= cright; ++r)
                complete += tiles[r][1] - tiles[r][0] + 1;

            // compute partial coverage
            partial = 0;
            if (r < n && tiles[r][0] <= cright)
                partial = cright - tiles[r][0] + 1;

            // update maximal cover length
            max_cover_len = max(max_cover_len, complete + partial);
            if (max_cover_len == carpetLen) { break; }

            // remove left
            if (tiles[l][1] <= cright)
                complete -= tiles[l][1] - tiles[l][0] + 1;
        }

        return max_cover_len;
    }
};
```

