I knew this problem as it was used in Amazon's online assessment. I think that it's quite hard; I am surprised that Amazon was giving it to new grads.

The solution of this problem is based on [84. Largest Rectangle in Histogram](https://leetcode.com/problems/largest-rectangle-in-histogram/). We use a mono-stack to find a subarray `[left, right]` where the current `pivot` is the smallest element. Then, we need to compute sum of all subarrays within `[left, right]` that include pivot. This is a tricky part. 

> Note: there is an easier solution (see Simplified Solution below). I could not see it rigth away, so it may be useful to read throught the original solution first.

#### Original Solution
Here, we compute prefix multiple - going from left and going from right.

We use prefix sum and prefix multiple to find sum of all subarrays from `pivot` to `left` (`left_sum`), and from `pivot` to `right` (`right_sum`). Then the sum of all subarrays is `right_sum * (pivot - left - 1) + left_sum * (right - pivot)`. Finally, we multiply this sum by the value of the pivot (smallest) element and add it to the result.

Let us look at this example: `[1,2,3,1,2,3,1]`. For `...1...` in the middle, we have the following subarrays that include it.

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/85b9fb05-8dd7-49f6-87d3-5347c6838933_1653196241.091054.png)

**Observation 1**
As you can see, the sum of all subarrays on the left is `18`, and it is included 3 times (into subarrays `...1]`, `...1, 2]` and `...1, 2, 3]`).

Similarly, the sum of all subarrays on the right is `7`, and it contributes to 4 subarrays (`[1, 2, 3, 1...`, `[2, 3, 1...`, `[3, 1...` and `[1...`). Therefore, sum of all `...1...` subarrays is `18 * 3 + 7 * 4`, which is `82`. 

**Observation 2**
We can see that `1` at position `0` is included once, `2` - twice, `3` - three times, and `1` - four times. So, our prefix multipe array (starting from the left) is computed as `1 * 1 + 2 * 2 + 3 * 3 + 1 * 4 + 2 * 5 + 3 * 6 + 1 * 7`. 

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/a63ed345-27fb-45b3-9948-6ab77b9ace2c_1653197229.068396.png)

Using prefix arrays, we can see that sum of left subarrays that ends at middle `1` is `18` (`18 - 0 - 0 * (7 - 0)`, and sum of right subarrays is `7` (`13 - 1 - 1 * (6 - 1)`).

To sumarize, the sum of subarrays from `i` ending at `j` is `pm_l[j + 1] - pm_l[i]` minus `i * (ps_l[j + 1] - ps_l[i])`. 

**C++**
```cpp
int totalStrength(vector<int>& s) {
    long long res = 0, sz = s.size(), mod = 1000000007;
    vector<int> ps_l(sz + 1), pm_l(sz + 1); // prefix sum and prefix mul from the left.
    vector<int> ps_r(sz + 1), pm_r(sz + 1); // ... from the right.
    vector<int> st; // mono-increasing stack.
    for (long long i = 0; i < sz; ++i) {
        ps_l[i + 1] = (ps_l[i] + s[i]) % mod;
        pm_l[i + 1] = (pm_l[i] + (i + 1) * s[i]) % mod;
    }
    for (int i = sz - 1; i >= 0; --i) {
        ps_r[i] = (ps_r[i + 1] + s[i]) % mod;
        pm_r[i] = (pm_r[i + 1] + (sz - i) * s[i]) % mod;
    }        
    for (int right = 0; right <= sz; ++right) {
        while(!st.empty() && (right == sz || s[st.back()] >= s[right])) {
            int pivot = st.back();
            st.pop_back();
            long long left = st.empty() ? 0 : st.back() + 1;
            long long left_sum = (mod + pm_l[pivot + 1] - pm_l[left] - left * (ps_l[pivot + 1] - ps_l[left]) % mod) % mod;
            long long right_sum = (mod + pm_r[pivot + 1] - pm_r[right] - (sz - right) * (ps_r[pivot + 1] - ps_r[right])) % mod;
            long long all_sum = (right_sum * (pivot - left + 1) + left_sum * (right - pivot)) % mod;
            res = (res + all_sum * s[pivot]) % mod;
        }
        st.push_back(right);
    }
    return res;
}
```

#### Simplified Solution
Same idea, but here we use prefix sum of prefix sum (`pps`). The formula is much simpler, but it's hard to understand why it works. I had the right intuition, but struggled with it for quite a while.

**C++**
```cpp
int totalStrength(vector<int>& s) {
    long long res = 0, sz = s.size(), mod = 1000000007;
    vector<int> st; // mono-increasing stack.
    vector<long long> pps(s.size() + 1);
    partial_sum(begin(s), end(s), begin(pps) + 1, [&](int s, int n){ return (s + n) % mod; });
    partial_sum(begin(pps), end(pps), begin(pps));
    for (int r = 0; r <= sz; ++r) {
        while(!st.empty() && (r == sz || s[st.back()] >= s[r])) {
            long long i = st.back(); st.pop_back();
            long long l = st.empty() ? -1 : st.back();
            res = (res + (mod + (pps[r] - pps[i]) * (i - l) % mod - (pps[i] - pps[max(0LL, l)]) * (r - i) % mod) * s[i]) % mod;
        }
        st.push_back(r);
    }
    return res;
}
```

