`minv[i]` : sum of minium value of subarrays ended at `i`
`dp[i]`: total sum of strengths of subarrays ended at `i`
`aggsum[i]`: aggregated sum of all subarrays ended at `i`
`sum[i]`: prefix sum ended at `i`

We use increasing mono stack and divide `dp[i]` into two parts: `left` , `right`
`left`: total strengths from minimm value at `arr[sk.back()]`
`right`: total strengths from current `arr[i]`

`dp[i]` = `left` + `right`
`lsum`: `sum[i]-sum[sk.back()])` -> sum from `arr[sk.back()+1 ... i]`
`asum`: `aggsum[i]-aggsum[sk.back()]` -> aggreated sum from `arr[sk.back()+1 ... i]`

if `arr = {1,2,3}`, then aggreated sum `aggsum[2]` = `1*1 + 2*2 + 3*3`, and `sum[2]` = `1+2+3`

`left` = `lsum*minv[sk.back()]` + `dp[sk.back()]`
`right` = `(asum-lsum*(sk.back()+1))` * `arr[i]`

Note that we make stack initialized to `-1` to avoid boundary check

Take `arr = {3,1,2}` for example, when we at `i = 2`, 
`left` = `dp[1] + minv[1]*lsum` = `5 + 2*2` = `9`, where` lsum = sum[2] - sum[sk.back()]`
`right` = `(asum - lsum * (sk.back()+1))` * `arr[2]` = `(6 - 2 - 2*2) * 2` = `4`, where `asum = aggsum[2] - aggsum[sk.back()]`
so `dp[2]` = `left` + `right` = `9+4` = `13`
