Coming up with the formula makes this a trick question; I suggest to reduce the size of the test cases, from 10 million numbers to 10 k or so, and this way, other reasonable code will work. It is hard to imagine any application using such extreme problem size. So, why make this a nightmare and trick question?

Below code solves 68 out of 80 test cases; for the rest of test cases, Time Limit Exceeded, liikely because of size.

```
class Solution {
    public int totalStrength(int[] strength) {

        int[] sumFromBegin = new int[strength.length + 1];
        int sum = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i < strength.length; i++) {
            sum += strength[i];
            sumFromBegin[i+1] = sum;
        }
        sumFromBegin[0] = 0;
        // sum(i , j) start inclusive, end inclusive --> sumFromBegin[j] - sumFromBegin[i]

        long grandSum = 0;
        int[] mins = new int[strength.length];
        int[] work = new int[strength.length];
        for (int i = 0; i < strength.length; i++) {
            work[i] = strength[i] * strength[i];
            grandSum += (int) work[i];
            mins[i] = strength[i];
        }        

        for (int k = 0; k < strength.length - 1; k++) {
            for (int j = 1; j < strength.length - k; j++) {
                int min = Math.min(mins[j],mins[j-1]);
                int localSum = sumFromBegin[j+k+1] - sumFromBegin[j-1];
                work[j-1] = min * localSum;
                mins[j-1] = min; // overwrite mins for next level
            }
            for (int i = 0; i < strength.length - k - 1; i++) {
                grandSum = (grandSum + work[i]) % 1000000007;
            }
        }
        return (int)(grandSum  % 1000000007);
    }
}
